erence>ES/I030700/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The sub-prime crisis has reduced the welfare of OECD societies directly as well as hurting wider communities via widespread recessions. Regulatory reforms currently being debated aim to reduce exposures to future tanking crisis risks and thus are of fundamental importance to the global economy.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The author's proposal will feed directly into such policy discussions. The robustness of early waming systems (EWSs) that forecast financial instability will be tested using an existing logit EWS developed with OECD data which has already highlighted important crisis determinants that were previously untested. Two issues will be specifically examined:&lt;/p>

&lt;ol>
 

 &lt;li>whether banking crisis determinants identified by the OECD model explain non-OECD crises&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>whether the OECD logit specification is robust to the attemative EWS estimators cited in the literature.&lt;/li>

&lt;/ol>

&lt;p>The attemative methodologies will include the Binary Recursive Tree and Signal Extraction approaches because the former detects non-linear interactions that drive crises and the latter allows comparison witti regulators' results.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-05-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2011-01-04</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>83858</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>3000</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>Bank leverage ratios, competition and risk - does Basel III go far enough?</gtr:description><gtr:end>2018-07-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Bank of England</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:fundingRef>RDC201614</gtr:fundingRef><gtr:id>18B42097-AD48-4073-8D97-448A081DA19D</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>58ab17ddd19c63.74788359</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Public</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2016-12-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>2205A89F-AF94-4647-A2D8-E6DD29F20737</gtr:id><gtr:title>Interest rate liberalization and capital adequacy in models of financial crises</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of F